York |isbn=978-1-350-07993-9 |ref=harv |language=en}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Rice |first1=Monika |title=What! Still Alive?!: Jewish Survivors in Poland and Israel Remember Homecoming |date=2017 |publisher=[[Syracuse University Press]] |location=Syracuse |isbn=978-0-8156-5419-3 |ref=harv |language=en}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Rubin |first1=Arnon |title=The Kielce Pogrom\u2014Spontaneity, Provocation or Part of a Country-Wide Scheme? |date=2004 |publisher=Tel Aviv University Press |location=Tel Aviv |isbn=978-965-555-144-0 |series=Facts and Fictions about the Rescue of the Polish Jewry During the Holocaust |ref=harv |language=en|volume=6}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Rubin |first1=Arnon|entry=D\u0119blin\u2013Irena|title=District Lublin| series=The Rise and Fall of the Jewish Communities in Poland and their Relics Today|volume=2 |date=2006|orig-year=1999 |publisher=Tel Aviv University Press |location=Tel Aviv |isbn=978-965-90744-2-6 |ref=harv |pp=89\u201393}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Silberklang |first1=David |title=Gates of Tears: the Holocaust in the Lublin District |date=2013 |publisher=Yad Vashem |location=Jerusalem |isbn=978-965-308-464-3 |language=English|title-link=Gates of Tears: the Holocaust in the Lublin District |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Snyder |first1=Timothy D. |authorlink1=Timothy D. Snyder |title=Bloodlands: Europe Between Hitler and Stalin |date=2012 |publisher=[[Basic Books]] |location=New York |isbn=978-0-465-03297-6 |ref=harv |language=en|title-link=Bloodlands: Europe Between Hitler and Stalin }}\n*{{cite book |last1=Weinstein |first1=Frederick |editor1-last=Schieb |editor1-first=Barbara |editor2-last=Voigt |editor2-first=Martina |title=Aufzeichnungen aus dem Versteck: Erlebnisse eines polnischen Juden 1939\u20131946 |trans-title=Notes from Hiding: Experiences of a Polish Jew 1939\u20131946 |date=2006 |publisher=Lukas Verlag|ref=harv |location=Berlin |isbn=978-3-936872-70-5 |language=de}} Secondhand account of first deportation on pages 206\u2013208.\n*{{cite encyclopedia |editor1-last=Miron |editor1-first=Gai |editor2-last=Shulhani |editor2-first=Shlomit |title=The Yad Vashem Encyclopedia of the Ghettos During the Holocaust |date=2009 |publisher=Yad Vashem |location=Jerusalem |isbn=978-965-308-345-5 |ref={{sfnref|Yad Vashem|2009}} |language=en|entry=D\u0119blin\u2013Irena|pp=156\u2013158|volume=1}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Zimmerman |first1=Joshua D. |authorlink1=Joshua D. Zimmerman |title=The Polish Underground and the Jews, 1939\u20131945 |date=2015 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |location=Cambridge |isbn=978-1-107-01426-8 |ref=harv |language=en}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book |translator-last=Altman |translator-first=Nolan |editor1-last=Stokfish |editor1-first=David |title=Sefer Deblin-Modzjitz |date=2003|orig-year=1969 |publisher=Arazi |location=Tel Aviv |url=https://www.jewishgen.org/Yizkor/deblin/deblin.html |trans-title=Deblin-Modzjitz [[Yizkor Book]]|isbn=978-0-657-14368-8}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Wenkart |first1=Hermann |title=Befehlsnotstand anders gesehen: Tatsachenbericht eines j\u00fcdischen Lagerfunktion\u00e4rs|trans-title=An Alternate View of [[Befehlsnotstand]]: Factual Report of a Jewish Camp Functionary |date=2013 |publisher=Books on Demand |isbn=978-3-7322-4754-7 |language=de|orig-year=1969}}\n<!-- *{{cite encyclopedia|title=Camps and Other Detention Facilities under the German Armed Forces|volume=4|series=[[Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos, 1933\u20131945]]|editor-last=Megargee|editor-first=Geoffrey |editor2-first= R\u00fcdiger|editor2-last= Overmans|editor3-first= Wolfgang|editor3-last= Vogt|date=upcoming}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia|title=Extermination, Labor, and Transit Camps for Jews|volume=6|series=[[Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos, 1933\u20131945]]|editor-last=Megargee|editor-first=Alexandra |editor-last=Lohse|date=upcoming}} -->\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://collections.ushmm.org/search/?f%5Bavailability%5D%5B%5D=digitized&f%5Bf_audiovisual%5D%5B%5D=all_fav&q=D%C4%99blin&search_field=all_fields Video and audio testimonies from Poles and Jews who lived in D\u0119blin during the war] (English, Polish, Hebrew) \n{{Holocaust Lublin}}\n{{Luftwaffe war crimes}}\n{{coord|51|33|48|N|21|51|53|E|display=title}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{good article}}\n\n[[Category:War crimes of the Wehrmacht]]\n[[Category:Ghettos in Lublin District]]\n[[Category:Pu\u0142awy County]]\n[[Category:1941 establishments in Poland]]\n[[Category:1942 disestablishments in Poland]]\n[[Category:Luftwaffe bases]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Ghetto in Poland}}\n\n{{Infobox concentration camp\n| type               = {{zwsp}}\n| name               = D\u0119blin\u2013Irena\n| image              = File:D\u0119blin\u2013Irena Ghetto.jpg\n| image size         = \n| caption            = After Jews were deported to [[Sobib\u00f3r extermination camp]] on 6 May 1942, bodies of those who were shot in the roundups were removed from the ghetto.{{sfn|Yad Vashem|2009|p=157}}\n| alt                = People drag a cart down an unpaved street in a town\n| known for          = One of the last labor camps  for Jews in [[Lublin Reservation|Lublin district]]\n| location           = Irena (adjacent to [[D\u0119blin]])\n| coordinates        = \n| built by           =\n| operated by        = [[Nazi Germany]]\n| commandant         =\n| original use       = \n| construction       = \n| in operation       = Early 1941 \u2013 28 October 1942\n| gas chambers       = \n| prisoner type      = Jews\n| inmates            = 5,800 (August 1942)\n| killed             = All but a few hundred\n| notable inmates    = [[Ignaz Bubis]]{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=66}}\n| notable books      = \n| website            = \n}}\n'''D\u0119blin\u2013Irena''' was a [[Nazi ghetto]] for Jews in Irena (merged into nearby [[D\u0119blin]] in 1953), a Polish town located in the [[Lublin District]] of the [[General Governorate]]. Initially, it was an [[Nazi ghettos#Types of ghettos|open ghetto]]; many Jews worked on labor projects for various local firms, especially the railway and the [[Luftwaffe]]. Beginning in May 1941, the ghetto became a collection center with Jews sent there from the [[Opole Ghetto|Opole]] and [[Warsaw Ghetto|Warsaw]] ghettos. In 1942, two thousand Jews [[deportation of Jews from Slovakia|arrived from Slovakia]] and hundreds more from nearby ghettos that had been liquidated.{{efn|name=liquidation|Liquidation refers to the Nazi action of shutting down a ghetto, with the inhabitants forced to move, deported, or murdered nearby.{{sfn|Aronson|Longerich|2001|p=194}}}}\n\nThe first deportation was in May 1942 and took around 2,500 Jews to [[Sobib\u00f3r extermination camp]]. In October that same year, the ghetto was liquidated; about 2,500 Jews were deported to [[Treblinka extermination camp]] while some 1,400 Jews were retained as inmates of forced-labor camps in the town. Unusually, the labor camp operated by the Luftwaffe\u2014employing, at its peak, about a thousand Jews\u2014was allowed to exist until 22 July 1944. One of the last Jewish labor camps in the Lublin District, it enabled hundreds of Jews to survive the Holocaust.\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Background ==\n[[File:Jews in D\u0119blin greet Pi\u0142sudski, 1920.png|thumb|left|alt= A line of Jewish men shown greeting Marshal J\u00f3zef Pi\u0142sudski| Jews in D\u0119blin greet Marshal [[J\u00f3zef Pi\u0142sudski]] after his capture of D\u0119blin during the [[Polish\u2013Soviet War]], 1920.]]\n[[D\u0119blin]] and Irena{{efn|The two municipalities, having long been considered one unit, were officially merged in 1953.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=636}}}} ({{lang-yi|\u05de\u05d0\u05d3\u05d6\u05e9\u05d9\u05e5}}, {{transl|yi|Modzhitz}}){{sfn|Yad Vashem|2009|p=156}} are located {{convert|68.7|km|sp=us}} northwest of [[Lublin]] in Poland,{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=636}} at the confluence of the [[Vistula]] and [[Wieprz]] rivers and at an important junction on the [[Lublin\u2013Warsaw rail line]].<ref name=\"MJP\" /> Local Jews supported the [[January Uprising]] in 1863. By the end of the nineteenth century, the area was a center of [[Hasidism]]; most Jews followed the [[Modzitz (Hasidic dynasty)|Modzitz]] dynasty, named after the town, and there were also [[Gur (Hasidic dynasty)|Gur Hasidim]]. Modzitz [[Rebbe]] Yisrael Taub settled in the town in 1889.<ref name=\"MJP\" />{{sfn|Rubin|2006|pp=89\u201390}} Other Jews were [[Jewish Labor Bund|Bundists]] or [[Zionists]].{{sfn|Yad Vashem|2009|p=156}} Many Jews made their living as peddlers, shopkeepers, or artisans (especially in leatherwork and metalwork) and later participated in the development of the town as a summer resort.{{sfn|Yad Vashem|2009|p=156}}{{sfn|Rubin|2006|p=90}}  In 1927, the civilian population of D\u0119blin and Irena was 4,860, including 3,060 Jews.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=636}} Since 1927, D\u0119blin housed the [[Polish Air Force Academy]],{{sfn|Protassewicz|2019|p=210}} whose airfield was one of the largest in Poland.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=63}} In 1936 and 1937, there were some incidents in which Polish merchants vandalized their Jewish competitors' shops.{{sfn|Rubin|2006|p=91}}\n<!--{{clear}}--->\n<!-- {{location mark |float=right|image=General Government for the occupied Polish territories (1941).png |upright=1.3| caption = Location of D\u0119blin\u2013Irena in the General Governorate|image_alt= Map of the administrative areas of the General Government showing location of D\u0119blin\u2013Irena Ghetto||label=D\u0119blin\u2013Irena |width=300|x%=34.5  |y%=28.5}} -->\n\nDuring the [[German invasion of Poland]], the [[Luftwaffe]] bombed D\u0119blin between 2 and 7&nbsp;September 1939,{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=636}} targeting the military airfield, [[Polish Army]] ammunition stores and a nearby bridge over the Vistula. Most Polish soldiers left the town on 7&nbsp;September; on 11&nbsp;September the remaining Polish forces detonated the ammunition and withdrew.{{sfn|Rubin|2006|p=91}} The [[Wehrmacht]] arrived  on 12 or 20&nbsp;September.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=636}}{{sfn|Yad Vashem|2009|p=156}} Many residents, both Poles and Jews, had fled to escape the aerial bombardment. In the following weeks, most returned at the urging of the Germans. The Jews found that their properties had been ransacked and plundered. They were conscripted into forced labor units that cleared up the bomb damage and repaired some of the buildings, and the Jewish community was forced to pay a fine of 20,000 [[z\u0142oty]].{{sfn|Yad Vashem|2009|p=156}}{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=636}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=59}} In late 1939, Jews were forced to wear armbands, and some were conscripted for forced labor in [[Janisz\u00f3w, Kra\u015bnik County|Janisz\u00f3w]], [[Be\u0142\u017cec, Lublin Voivodeship|Be\u0142\u017cec]], and [[Paw\u0142owice, Lublin Voivodeship |Paw\u0142owice]].{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=637}}\n\nThe {{lang|de|[[Judenrat]]}} (\"Jewish Council\") was formed at the end of the year{{sfn|Yad Vashem|2009|p=156}}{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=636}}\u2014later than other {{lang|de|Judenr\u00e4te}} in the region{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|pp=58\u201359}}\u2014and had its offices on Bankowa Street.{{sfn|Rubin|2006|p=91}} The first {{lang|de|Judenrat}} officials worked to reduce the impact of German demands and warned ghetto residents of searches. The first chair of the {{lang|de|Judenrat}}, Leizer Teichman, and the secretary were expelled in 1941, after trying to bribe policemen. The {{lang|de|Judenrat}} was run temporarily by Kalman Fris, who resigned after a few months and was replaced by Vevel Shulman in August and then a Konin native named Drayfish in September 1941.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=637}} According to Israeli historian [[David Silberklang]], \"Szymon Drabfisz\" was the first chair and Teichman the second.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=67}} The [[Jewish Ghetto Police]] maintained order in the ghetto, and on the outside it was guarded by a {{lang|de|[[Sonderdienst]]}} (\"Special Services\") unit consisting of local {{lang|de|[[Volksdeutsche]]}} and [[Trawniki men|Ukrainian auxiliaries]]. The {{lang|de|Sonderdienst}} unit was known for beating, humiliating, and  killing ghetto inmates.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=637}}\n{{clear}}\n\n== Ghetto ==\n\n[[File:Irena, Lublin map.png|thumb|upright=1.3|alt=Map of Irena showing some ghetto boundaries and an airfield | Map of Irena. Ok\u00f3lna Street, the Irenka River, Bankowa, and Staromiejska Streets shown. Airfield in lower right.]]\nA ghetto was established in Irena in November 1940{{sfn|Yad Vashem|2009|p=157}} or early 1941, probably on the orders of Kurt Lenk, the region's new land commissioner.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=637}} Officially, it was not a ghetto but a Jewish residence restriction.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|pp=211, 214}} Some Jews were forced to move from their homes to the ghetto. The motive was probably to keep Jews away from the two nearby military installations, a Luftwaffe airfield and a Wehrmacht base, which were filled with troops in preparation for the [[Operation Barbarossa|1941 invasion of the Soviet Union]]. (The decree establishing the ghetto was not formally issued until 1942).{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=637}} Until 1942,{{sfn|Yad Vashem|2009|p=156}} Irena was an [[Nazi ghettos#Types of ghettos|open ghetto]] (there was no physical fence, although the penalty for unauthorized departure was death) consisting of six streets. Its boundaries were initially Ok\u00f3lna Street, the Irenka River, Bankowa, and Staromiejska Streets. Staromiejska Street was removed from the ghetto in September 1942; its residents moved to Bankowa. Initially, Poles were allowed to enter and perhaps live in the ghetto, so many of the Jews were able to survive by trading material goods for food with them.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=637}} A Polish-language secular school, run by Aida Milgroijm-Citronbojm, instructed 70 to 100 pupils.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=637}}{{sfn|Rubin|2006|p=92}}\n\nIn late 1941, Poles were banned from entering the ghetto, resulting in waste piling up and [[typhus]] and [[dysentery]] epidemics. The sick were treated at a thirty-bed hospital run by Isaar Kawa, a doctor from [[Konin]]; with the help of Polish doctors, medicines were imported from Warsaw.{{sfn|Yad Vashem|2009|p=157}}{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=637}}  Simultaneously,  new restrictions were imposed by the Germans: the use of stoves was banned, winter clothing requisitioned, and fuel imports forbidden.{{sfn|Rubin|2006|p=92}}{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=637}} More Jews began to leave the ghetto to obtain essentials, resulting in twenty young women being shot after being captured.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}} Because conditions were better in Lublin District than in Warsaw, some Jews fled to towns there including D\u0119blin\u2013Irena;{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=196}} twenty Jews were shot for being unregistered refugees. The {{lang|de|Judenrat}}{{'}}s command altered again as Drayfish was executed, accused of filing complaints with the Pu\u0142awy County administration; he was replaced by the businessman Yisrael Weinberg.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}\n\nIn March 1941, 3,750 Jews lived in the ghetto, including 565 who were not from the area. These consisted mainly of Jews expelled from [[Pu\u0142awy]] and the [[Warthegau]] region, as well as some Jews who had come to live with relatives to avoid being trapped in the [[Warsaw Ghetto]]. Overcrowding was severe; there were 7\u201315 people per room. More Jews arrived in May 1941: 1,000 from the ghettos at Warsaw, [[Cz\u0119stochowa Ghetto|Cz\u0119stochowa]], and [[Opole Ghetto|Opole]], although they were not housed in the ghetto but at work sites in the area.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=637}} On 13 and 14&nbsp;May 1942, two transports totalling 2,042 [[Slovak Jews]]  [[List of Holocaust transports from Slovakia|arrived from Pre\u0161ov]].{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler |1991| p=166}} Although they brought food with them, they were unused to the harsh conditions and many died of typhus due to the poor sanitation.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=62}} More than 2,000 Jews were brought to D\u0119blin\u2013Irena from nearby towns, having survived the liquidation{{efn|name=liquidation}} of their communities because they had been selected to work. These included 300 people from [[Ryki]], 300 from [[Gniewosz\u00f3w, Masovian Voivodeship|Gniewosz\u00f3w]] and [[Zwole\u0144]], and a group from [[St\u0119\u017cyca, Lublin Voivodeship|St\u0119\u017cyca]]. Other Jews had entered the ghetto after escaping roundups in [[Baran\u00f3w, Lublin Voivodeship|Baran\u00f3w]], Ryki, Gniewosz\u00f3w, and [[Adam\u00f3w, \u0141uk\u00f3w County|Adam\u00f3w]] (from early October). In August, 5,800 Jews were reported to be living in the ghetto, of whom only 1,800 were from D\u0119blin.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}\n\n== Forced labor ==\n[[File:Soviet soldiers mass grave, German war prisoners concentration camp in Deblin, German-occupied Poland.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2| left|alt=Exhumed mass grave holding remains of Soviet soldiers at Stalag 307 | Exhumed mass grave at Stalag 307 ([[D\u0119blin Fortress]]), where an estimated 80,000 Soviet prisoners were imprisoned. All died within a few months of starvation and disease.{{sfn|Snyder|2012|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=maEfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA180 180]}}{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|pp=399\u2013400}}]]\nUntil late 1942, Jews earned wages as forced laborers, except those who were conscripted by the muncipality for tasks such as street cleaning or snow clearing. Many Jews worked for German companies such as Schwartz and [[Hochtief]], which were hired to do construction on the military bases in the town. Schultz was also under contract for construction on the [[Ostbahn (General Government)|Ostbahn]].{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=637}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=61}} [[D\u0119blin Fortress]], which had been taken over by the Wehrmacht and where around 200 Jews from the ghetto worked,{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=63}} was the site of [[Stalag 307]], a [[German mistreatment of Soviet prisoners of war|Soviet prisoner-of-war camp]] from 10&nbsp;July 1941.{{sfn|Rubin|2006|p=92}}{{sfn|Snyder|2012|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=maEfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA180 180]}}{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|pp=274, 399}} The Jews could favorably compare their situation to that of the Soviet prisoners.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=274}} The Jews from D\u0119blin\u2013Irena tried to take the best jobs; 200 of the Slovak deportees ended up working for the municipality. Another 200 of the Slovaks worked for the Schultz firm following an expansion.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}} Survivors recalled that although German soldiers supervising the forced laborers tended to treat them relatively well, some Polish supervisors beat Jews, and the Ukrainian guards at the railway camp were especially harsh.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=70}}\n\nIn May 1941, in preparation for the invasion of the Soviet Union, the Luftwaffe commissioned the firm Autheried to improve the airfield.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=64}} They recruited 200 Jewish workers in Opole and had success with many Viennese Jews. Deported to Opole in February 1941, the Viennese wanted to escape the harsh conditions there.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=64}} These Jews, as well as another four hundred recruited in D\u0119blin\u2013Irena and the [[Lipowa 7]] camp in Lublin,{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=637}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=64}} and 500 Polish workers, worked twelve hours a day levelling the runway and building roads, walls, air-raid shelters, and earth fortifications. They also built a barbed-wire-enclosed complex adjacent to the runway for craftsmen to work.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=64}} Following the completion of the project in October, the workers were dispersed to various projects around the town, an action which may have been related to the typhus epidemic.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=637}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=64}} Some of the Jews from Vienna stayed at the airfield, having obtained permits to work on gravel transportation and building fuel tanks; they were the nucleus for the later labor camp. After the deportation of 6&nbsp;May 1942, additional Jews tried to secure permits, often fictitious ones obtained through bribery, to avoid deportation. By October 1942, the camp had 543 legal residents.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=64}} At this point there were five forced-labor camps around D\u0119blin: the Luftwaffe camp, the fortress, the train station (300 Jews), Lipova Street (200 Jews and Poles), and another near the municipal boundary (300 Jews).{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=400}}\n\n== Deportation, murder, and liquidation ==\n===First deportation (6 May 1942)===\nThe first deportation was on 6&nbsp;May 1942,{{sfn|Weinstein|2006|p=459}}{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}} to clear space for the Slovak deportees who arrived a week later.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=608}}{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}{{sfn|Musia\u0142|2000|p=244}} A force composed of German and Ukrainian police and a few German SS and Ukrainian SS auxiliaries ordered Jews to assemble in the main square at 09:00&nbsp;hours.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}} According to [[Yad Vashem]], the [[Blue Police]] also participated.{{sfn|Yad Vashem|2009|p=158}} Probably because the Luftwaffe was seeking permission to recruit more laborers, the Jews had to wait for five hours. At 14:00, 1,000 Jews who already had work assignments were separated, and local employers began recruiting an additional 200\u2013500 Jews. Forty or fifty people were killed trying to cross over to the working group.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}} Most of the Jews from neighboring communities{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=308}} and 2,300 to 2,500 from D\u0119blin\u2014mainly the elderly and families with small children\u2014were marched to the [[D\u0119blin train station]] (some {{convert|2.5|km|sp=us}} away) at 18:00 and sent to [[Sobib\u00f3r extermination camp]].{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=61}} The victims were beaten, and those who could not keep up were shot. Only late in the night were the Jews selected for labor allowed to return home. Every family was affected.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|pp=61\u201362}} After the deportation, the bodies of the dead were collected at the synagogue and removed from the ghetto in carts.{{sfn|Yad Vashem|2009|p=157}}\n\nDuring the next two days, more than four thousand Jews from north Pu\u0142awy County\u2014200 from [[Bobrowniki]] (6&nbsp;May),  1,800 from Ryki (7&nbsp;May), 125 from St\u0119\u017cyca (7&nbsp;May), 1,500 from Baran\u00f3w (8&nbsp;May) and 500 from [[\u0141ysobyki]] (8&nbsp;May)\u2014were also marched to D\u0119blin and deported to Sobib\u00f3r.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|pp=308, 317}} This was half of a countywide extermination action in Pu\u0142awy County\u2014the first in a series of systematic, countywide deportations in the Lublin district. The county's administrator, {{ill|Alfred Brandt|de|Alfred Brandt (Landrat)}} ordered it shortly after Sobib\u00f3r became operational.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=60}}{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=309}}\n\n===Second deportation (15 October 1942)===\nThe next deportation, which coincided with the liquidation of the two remaining ghettos in Pu\u0142awy (Opole and Ko\u0144skowola),{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=60}}{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=329}} took place on 15&nbsp;October 1942; the previous day, all workers had been ordered to remain at their workplaces. Under the command of {{lang|de|SS-Obersturmf\u00fchrer}} Grossman; gendarmes, Luftwaffe soldiers, and police auxiliaries rounded up the remaining Jewish population.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}} Many Jews tried to enter the Luftwaffe camp, which at that time had 543 official residents, but they were turned away by the Jewish police there. Talia Farkash estimates that about 500, including 60\u201390 young children, managed to get in, mostly by paying bribes.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=66}} Silberklang's estimate is that 1,000 Jews entered the camp, including 280 women and 100 children.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=400}} The Jewish elder, Hermann Wenkert, later claimed that if he had allowed non-registered Jews entry, and they were discovered, everyone in the camp would have been killed. Instead, he bribed the Germans to obtain legal permits for an additional 400 Jews, which were mostly given to the wives and children of current residents.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=66}}\n\nMany of the Slovak Jews, not knowing what to expect, had lingered in the ghetto while packing their bags. About 215 to 500 Jews were shot while clearing the houses.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=63}} Between 2,000{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=63}} and 2,500 people were deported to [[Treblinka extermination camp]]; mostly the Slovaks.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=329}} Members of the {{lang|de|Judenrat}}, Jewish police, and their families, about 100 total, were retained to clean up the ghetto.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=63}} Perhaps another 100 Jews were hiding illegally in the ghetto.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=63}} On 28 October, the remaining Jews were sent to the Schultz labor camp, and the ghetto was officially liquidated. Either on that day or within the next few weeks, 1,000 people were removed from the labor camps, including the 200 workers at D\u0119blin Fortress and 200\u2013500 of the Luftwaffe's workers.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=63}} They were deported to Ko\u0144skowola{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=63}} or Treblinka.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}\n\nAfter this, Farkash estimates that there were about 1,400 Jews were still alive in the labor camps around Irena.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=63}} Estimates of the number at the Luftwaffe camp range frmo 1,000 (''[[Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos]]''){{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}} to 2,000 (Silberklang),{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=400}} with another 300 at a railway camp near the passenger station, and 120 at another camp near the railway loading station.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=63}} During May or July 1943, most of the remaining prisoners in the railway camps were deported to [[Poniatowa concentration camp|Poniatowa]] via the transit ghetto in Ko\u0144skowola; the rest were deported in late 1943.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=63}}  In the remaining labor camps in Pu\u0142awy County, where hundreds of Jews were still alive, they were murdered during [[Operation Harvest Festival]] (2\u20133&nbsp;November 1943). This operation also killed the prisoners of Poniatowa but did not affect the Jews at the Luftwaffe camp in D\u0119blin\u2013Irena,{{sfn|Farkash|2014|pp=60\u201361, 63}}{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=402}} who were unaware of it.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=409}} Following Operation Harvest Festival, there were ten labor camps for Jews in the Lublin District with more than 10,000 Jews still alive.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=365}}\n\n== Luftwaffe camp ==\n===Camp leader===\n[[File:UT 2 w Szkole Orlat w Deblinie.jpg|thumb|alt= Polish Air Force Academy airfield with four planes and a number of men around them |[[Polish Air Force Academy]] in D\u0119blin, 1947]]\nThe camp leader ({{lang-de|[[Lager\u00e4lteste]]}}) at the Luftwaffe camp was Hermann Wenkert, a Jewish lawyer from Vienna who had been deported to Opole in 1941 and came to Irena with the volunteers.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=65}}  According to Wenkert's account,{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=402}} soon after his arrival he happened upon Eduard Bromofsky, an Austrian Luftwaffe officer with whom Wenkert had served during World War I. Bromofsky convinced the commander of the camp to promote Wenkert to his position. Even after Bromofsky was reassigned, the relationships that Wenkert had cultivated with the German authorities enabled him to retain his position.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=65}} Wenkert populated the administration with other Viennese Jews, insisted on extra rations for himself and his family, and had his family transferred from Opole to Irena. Because of his close association with the German authorities and use of his position for personal benefit, some survivors considered him to be a collaborator.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=65}}{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=401}} When it was possible, Wenkert negotiated with the authorities and paid bribes to avoid punishment; he also consulted respected prisoners in cases where the matter had not come to German attention. However, when he thought there was no other option and the survival of the camp was in the balance, Wenkert turned Jews accused of wrongdoing over to the Germans even though he knew that this would result in their deaths.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=67}} In general, German-speaking Jews had a more positive impression of him than the local Jews, who spoke Yiddish.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=66}} According to Silberklang, both views of Wenkert may be true: that he tried to secure benefits for himself personally while also working to keep the other Jewish prisoners alive.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|pp=401\u2013402}}\n\n===Conditions===\nConditions were relatively good compared to other camps.{{sfn|Rubin|2006|p=93}}{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=365}} Residents received food rations of about 1,700 [[kilocalories]] daily (enough to live), weekly baths, medical care, and were allowed to practice their religion.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=78}}{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=400}} The presence of 100 young children\u2014whose existence was justified by increasing the productivity of their parents\u2014was particularly unusual and not equalled elsewhere in the Lublin District after Operation Harvest Festival. The children received education in Polish, but had to hide when the SS conducted inspections.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|pp=72\u201373}} According to Israeli historian Talia Farkash, Wenkert's positive relationship with the camp command was partially responsible for the good conditions.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=69}} Wenkert managed to get religious Jews exempted from working on [[Shabbat]] and allowed a [[chevra kadisha]] society to operate, burying the dead according to Jewish law. In 1943, about 80 Jews (including Wenkert) received kosher food for the week of [[Passover]].{{sfn|Farkash|2014|pp=73\u201374}}{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=401}}\n\nThe camp had three German commanders, all at the rank of Sergeant Major:  Kattengel (through March 1943), Dusy, and Rademacher (during the last two months). Although Kattengel was distrusted, because he roamed the camp with a dog and whip, both Dusy and Rademacher were described positively by survivors. Dusy even arranged for one woman to receive treatment at a German hospital after she was badly injured. Wiszniewski, a local {{lang|de|Volkesdeutscher}}, was the lead foreman of the Jewish laborers and did not mistreat them. Autheried engineer Kozak brought food to the Jews he worked with.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|pp=69\u201370}} Both theft and having foreign currency were punishable by death. Punishment could be excessive and arbitrary\u2014nine Jews were shot for causing a fire, even though it was proved to be accidental\u2014but less so than other Nazi camps.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|pp=74\u201375}} According to Farkash, in 1943, Wenkert allowed a group of [[Jewish partisans]] seeking refuge from a hostile unit of the Polish [[Home Army]] resistance group into the camp.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=67}} The Slovak Jews at the camp were the last major group to survive of the almost 40,000 Slovak Jews deported to the Lublin District in 1942.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler |1991| p=159}}{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=296}} The [[The Holocaust in Slovakia#Hiatus (1943)|Jews remaining in Pre\u0161ov]] hired couriers (non-Jews from the Polish\u2013Slovak border) to travel to the camp regularly until it was dissolved, carrying letters and bringing valuables and money. A committee was formed in the camp to distribute the aid among the Slovak Jews. Cases of theft by Polish Jews led to friction between the two communities.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler |1991|p=159}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=70}}\n\nDespite the relatively good conditions, some Jews tried to escape because they feared that the camp would be liquidated. The Luftwaffe camp command imposed [[collective punishment]] to deter escapees.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=74}} According to a 1943 [[Home Army]] report, the local Polish population was hostile to Jewish fugitives. The organization itself accused Jews of joining Communist partisan groups and stealing from Polish peasants.{{sfn|Zimmerman|2015|pp=213, 361}} Most Jews who tried to escape were captured, and others returned to the camp.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=74}} Several members of the Kowalczyk family were honored as [[Righteous Among the Nations]] for sheltering Jews who had escaped from the camp.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kowalczyk family |url=https://righteous.yadvashem.org/?search=Deblin&searchType=righteous_only&language=en&itemId=4034962&ind=1 |website=The Righteous Among the Nations Database |publisher=[[Yad Vashem]]|accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref> \u00c1rp\u00e1d Szab\u00f3, a Hungarian military doctor, was similarly recognized for smuggling a Slovak Jewish couple to Hungary.<ref>{{cite web |title=Szab\u00f3 \u00c1rp\u00e1d |url=https://righteous.yadvashem.org/?search=Deblin&searchType=righteous_only&language=en&itemId=4044388&ind=2 |website=The Righteous Among the Nations Database |publisher=[[Yad Vashem]] |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Liquidation===\n[[File:Cz\u0119stochowa - Hasag-Pelcery plaque 2.jpg|thumb|alt=Plaque with Star of David and Hebrew letters|left|Memorial plaque at the former HASAG camp in Cz\u0119stochowa]]\nThe camp was liquidated on 22&nbsp;July 1944, the same day that the Red Army reached Lublin.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}} At the time of the deportation, some 800 to 900 Jews were still alive, of whom 400 to 600 were from  D\u0119blin\u2013Irena,{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}} 40 from Vienna,{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=70}} and 70 to 80  from Slovakia.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler |1991|p=159}} Two{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=75}} or three{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=409}} transports departed from D\u0119blin\u2013Irena on 17 and 22&nbsp;July.  (Silberklang reports a third on 20 July).{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=409}} Since no one was willing to volunteer, the first transport carried about 200 people who had few connections in the camp, including single adults and fifteen children between three and six years of age. On the orders of camp security officer Georg Bartenschlager, the fifteen children were shot upon their arrival in Cz\u0119stochowa. The rest of the prisoners, including Wenkert and 33 young children, departed on the second transport with Rademacher, the German camp commander, who carried a letter of protection from the airfield commander.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=75}} About fifty Jews escaped from the camp during the evacuation, but most were killed. The second transport arrived in Cz\u0119stochowa on 25 July; the young children were kept separated for two and a half days but were not killed. The reason for this is not clear, but likely involved negotiations with Bartenschlager.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|pp=76\u201377}} In Cz\u0119stochowa, the Jews worked at the four  [[Hugo Schneider AG]] plants. Some were deported to [[Buchenwald concentration camp|Buchenwald]] and [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]] in January 1945 while others were liberated by the Red Army.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=77}} About half survived.{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}\n\nAccording to Farkash, the airfield camp at D\u0119blin\u2013Irena is a \"singular case\" in the Lublin district and possibly in the entirety of occupied Poland.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=58}} One unusual aspect of the camp was that it was run from start to finish by the Luftwaffe rather than the SS, although during 1943 and 1944, the SS tried to expand its role.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=68}} According to Silberklang, being run by the Wehrmacht helped to ensure the camp's survival.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=364}} However, other camps (such as three in Zamo\u015b\u0107 county) were run by the Luftwaffe and yet were still liquidated before the end of 1943.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|pp=68, 78}} Another reason was the importance of Jewish workers at D\u0119blin to the German war effort,{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=411}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|pp=78\u201379}} which was continually emphasized by Wenkert in his dealings with the Germans. Overall, luck played a major role in the fortuitous combination of Jewish leadership, relatively friendly Germans, and the evacuation of the camp to Cz\u0119stochowa rather than [[Auschwitz-Birkenau]].{{sfn|Farkash|2014|pp=78\u201379}} Ninety-nine percent of the Jews from Lublin District were killed in the Holocaust,{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|p=431}} but hundreds from D\u0119blin\u2013Irena survived the war.{{sfn|Farkash|2014|pp=78\u201379}}\n\n== Aftermath ==\nD\u0119blin was liberated by the [[1st Polish Army]] by 27&nbsp;July 1944.{{sfn|Weinstein|2006|p=536}} Some of the Jewish survivors, who attempted to return home in January 1945, were told by the local [[Milicja Obywatelska]] chief that it was illegal for them to settle in town.{{sfn|Rubin|2004|p=88}}{{sfn|Rice|2017|p=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=L0MwDwAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PP1&dq=D%C4%99blin+1942+jews&ots=4YMln6eUay&sig=R5NCwbZQA85AeAzLL2NuAiYSdwA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=D%C4%99blin&f=false 29]}}{{sfn|Ko\u017ami\u0144ska-Frejlak|2014|p=154}} In March 1945, survivors \u0141aja, Gitla and Fryda Luksemburg were murdered with the involvement of local police.{{sfn|Krzy\u017canowski|2013|p=253}}<ref name=\"Miasto\" /> Ester Kaminska suffered repeated harassment and extortion from local Poles, one of whom had obtained her family's bakery from the Nazis, which led to her departure to Palestine in 1947.{{sfn|Rice|2017|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=L0MwDwAAQBAJ&oi=fnd&pg=PP1&dq=D%C4%99blin+1942+jews&ots=4YMln6eUay&sig=R5NCwbZQA85AeAzLL2NuAiYSdwA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=D%C4%99blin&f=false 119\u2013120]}} Other Jews received threatening letters. By 1947, no Jews remained in the town,<ref name=\"Miasto\" /> which is still the case in the twenty-first century.<ref name=MJP>{{cite web |title=Deblin Modrzyc (Irena) |url=https://dbs.bh.org.il/place/deblin-modrzyc-irena-demblin |website=[[Museum of the Jewish People at Beit Hatfutsot]] |accessdate=23 December 2019 |ref={{sfnref|Museum of the Jewish People|2019}} |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223110628/https://dbs.bh.org.il/place/deblin-modrzyc-irena-demblin |archive-date=23 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> {{as of| 2011}}, the {{ill|D\u0119blin Synagogue|pl|Synagoga w D\u0119blinie}} was in poor condition and being considered for demolition.{{sfn|Bergman|Jagielski|2014|p=565}} A memorial plaque was unveiled in 2015.<ref name=Miasto>{{cite news |title=Ods\u0142oni\u0119cie tablicy pami\u0105tkowej |url=https://www.deblin.pl/kultura/n,9524,odsloniecie-tablicy-pamiatkowej.html |accessdate=31 December 2019 |work=Miasto D\u0119blin |date=27 October 2015 |language=pl|trans-title=Unveiling of a commemorative plaque }}</ref>\n\n[[Ignaz Bubis]], a former prisoner of the ghetto,{{sfn|Crago|2012|p=638}}{{sfn|Farkash|2014|p=63}} was the chairman of the [[Central Council of Jews in Germany]] from 1992 to 1999.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Friedlander |first1=Albert |title=Obituary: Ignatz Bubis |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-ignatz-bubis-1113062.html |accessdate=25 December 2019 |work=The Independent |date=16 August 1999 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191225093733/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/obituary-ignatz-bubis-1113062.html |archive-date=25 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin|35em|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia|entry=Final Solution: Preparation and Implementation|last1=Aronson|first1=Shlomo|last2=Longerich|first2=Peter|author2link=Peter Longerich |authorlink=Shlomo Aronson (historian)|pp=184\u2013198 |editor1-last=Laqueur |editor1-first=Walter |editor-link=Walter Laqueur|editor2-last=Baumel |editor2-first=Judith Tydor |title=Holocaust Encyclopedia |date=2001 |publisher=Yale University Press |location=New Haven |language=en|isbn=978-0-300-08432-0|ref=